    <h2>CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION</h2>
    
    <h3>1.1 Background of the Study</h3>
    <p>The global higher education landscape is currently undergoing a profound digital transformation, often referred to in literature as "Education 4.0." Universities are increasingly abandoning legacy, paper-based administration methods in favor of integrated Student Information Systems (SIS) and Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) tools. These systems often handle enrollment, course registration, and basic grading efficiently. However, the specific, high-stakes niche of <strong>Graduation Clearance</strong> often remains a manual outlier, disconnected from the central digital ecosystem.</p>
    <p>In the specific context of the Faculty of Computing and Information Management, the administration of the Bachelor of Business Information and Communication Technology (BBICT) program faces unique operational challenges. The curriculum is inherently dynamic; elective courses are frequently added or removed based on industry trends, and credit weightings may shift slightly between academic years. Manually tracking which version of the curriculum applies to which student cohort (e.g., the Class of 2022 vs. the Class of 2026) is a complex task.</p>
    <p>Currently, the Registrar's office relies on a disparate set of ad-hoc tools: Excel spreadsheets for grade aggregation, physical folders for storage of medical and financial receipts, and personal email for communication. This fragmented approach is sustainable for small cohorts of 20-30 students. However, as enrollment numbers have surged to over 200 graduating students per year, this manual infrastructure has become a severe logistical bottleneck. Staff members spend weeks manually calculating Great Point Averages (GPAs), often recounting credits for the same student multiple times to ensure accuracy.</p>
    <p>"Degreefi" was conceived to bridge this specific gap. By digitizing the "last mile" of the student journey, it provides a dedicated, intelligent interface that democratizes access to graduation data.</p>

    <h3>1.2 Statement of the Problem</h3>
    <p>The current operational framework for graduation clearance is characterized by several critical inefficiencies, which this project identifies as the core "Problem Space." These issues can be categorized into four distinct pillars:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Information Asymmetry and Lack of Transparency:</strong> Students currently operate in a state of blindness regarding their official standing. A student might believe they have completed all credits, only to be informed during the final week that a specific elective from Year 2 was never officially recorded due to a clerical error.</li>
        <li><strong>Decentralized Verification Silos:</strong> The clearance process is inherently cross-departmental, requiring verification from multiple independent bodies (Bursary, Library, Department, Sports) that operate in data silos.</li>
        <li><strong>Administrative Latency and Workload:</strong> The manual audit of a single student's file takes a skilled registrar approximately 20-30 minutes. Multiplied by a cohort of 200 students, this represents hundreds of man-hours of repetitive labor.</li>
        <li><strong>Data Integrity and Security Risks:</strong> Physical documents can be lost, damaged, or forged. There is no digital audit trail to verify who signed a form and when.</li>
    </ol>
    <p><strong>Research Question:</strong> <em>How can a web-based information system be architected to automate the complex, rule-based logic of graduation eligibility while providing a unified, secure, and transparent platform for multi-departmental clearance?</em></p>

    <h3>1.3 Objectives of the Project</h3>
    <h4>1.3.1 General Objective</h4>
    <p>The primary goal of this project is to analyze, design, and develop "Degreefi," a robust, secure, and user-centric web application that digitizes the entire graduation clearance workflow for the BBICT program.</p>
    <h4>1.3.2 Specific Objectives</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>To Develop an Automated Audit Algorithm:</strong> To design and implement a logic engine that dynamically fetches a student's full academic transcript and compares it against the master BBICT curriculum.</li>
        <li><strong>To Implement a Unified Digital Clearance Portal:</strong> To create a secure, cloud-based file upload system where students can submit digital proofs for various non-academic requirements.</li>
        <li><strong>To Create a Real-Time Administrative Dashboard:</strong> To build a control panel that provides a bird's-eye view of the entire graduating cohort, identifying "At-Risk" students.</li>
        <li><strong>To Integrate a Seamless Notification System:</strong> To implement in-app notifications for instant, contextual feedback on document status.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1.4 Scope and Limitations</h3>
    <h4>1.4.1 Project Scope</h4>
    <p>The project encompasses the full Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC), including Frontend development (React.js), Backend development (Node.js/Express.js), Database Management (MongoDB Atlas), and core functionalities like User Registration, Record Entry, and Admin Verification.</p>
    <h4>1.4.2 Project Limitations</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Lack of Legacy Integration:</strong> The system acts as an overlay and does not integrate via API with the university's legacy ERP due to security restrictions.</li>
        <li><strong>Curriculum Specificity:</strong> The logic is optimized for BBICT rules; scaling to other faculties would require code refactoring.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1.5 Significance of the Study</h3>
    <p>The project offers value by improving <strong>Operational Efficiency</strong> for administration, providing <strong>Empowerment and Agency</strong> for students, and promoting <strong>Sustainability</strong> by reducing paper waste.</p>
